T1  - A reexamination of the neoclassical trade model under uncertainty
AU  - Hoff, Karla
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 36
IS  - 1
SP  - 1
EP  - 27
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/02/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(94)90055-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199694900558
AB  - This paper presents a model that pinpoints the exact places and reasons that the propositions of the Heckscher-Ohlin-Samuelson model break down under uncertainty. Within the model, if preferences exhibit decreasing absolute risk aversion, (i) a capital-poor country tends to obtain lower revenues from its resources than the same resources would yield in capital-rich countries, (ii) if there is one riskless and one risky sector, a capital-abundant country tends to have a comparative advantage in the risky sector, and (iii) the pattern of trade depends on the intranational as well as the international distribution of endowments.
